"Yes, sir. They should be on their way now; we've given them time to get rations from the mess." At exactly 5:00, Company Exodus was assembled at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are deploying to FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We need to support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to quell the insurgency. From there, we will have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units and board the transports."
The company dispersed, each person returning to their unit, and the sergeants had them climb onto the tanks. Cohren climbed aboard one of the armored vehicles at the front of the convoy and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he didn't know much about them. Sitting on the side with his legs dangling, he adjusted his pack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, has Harris always had Snowball?" asked Nemic as they settled in.
"Are you talking about the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure."
Cohren glanced toward one of the tanks and spotted Harris with his unit. From the back of his pack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken shaking its head to look around.
"Yeah, he always does," replied Cohren as the tank's turret creaked open to let his commander pass.
"All the tanks were on their way," declared the commander calmly but clearly through his helmet. The engines of a platoon of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to move forward. The Kronos on which Cohren was riding jolted when its brakes were released and it started moving to join the formation. The tanks deployed in a V formation to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud was still there.
After about an hour, one of the new recruits, named Orson in memory of Cohren, spoke up. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the beginning of the war, haven't you?"
"Yep, Operation Firestorm," replied Cohren. "We thought we'd wrap it up in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimating is a weak word," said Nemic, joining the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we anticipated. They managed to bring down the UFS Revenant within the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Shit, we should see it from the road we're on."
"Well, I'll hold firm for the Federation," said Orson, a bit provocatively. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that young recruits like you, who are 18 years old, take cover as soon as they hear a shot," said Craith.
"I think we'll soon find out," said Corhen, laughing. Orson did not continue the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We are detecting thermal signatures at approximately 300 meters, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed onto the top of the vehicle and put on his optical glasses. By activating thermal vision, he was able to see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Yep, I see them," replied Cohren via his throat microphone.
"Enemies?", asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"It's impossible to say," declared Cohren. He activated his microphone and said, "Exodus team, don't fire unless you're fired upon, let's get them out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures changed from blurry spots into more distinct shapes. As they drew even closer, one of them ran toward something, grabbed it, and then dashed back toward the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took up firing positions.
"We have contacts!" Shaw shouted into the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the ridge. The bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while soldiers jumped from the vehicles to take cover behind them. An anti-tank missile whistled past and crashed behind the formation, exploding and sending debris onto one of the vehicles. Another missile struck the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew scrambled out and dove for cover as the ammunition caught fire.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 275 meters." "Fire," shouted the tank platoon commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire; their shells flew toward the ridge and exploded, throwing mud and rocks into the air.
"Send the Senti," cried Knoxx, who was observing the ridge through his binoculars. The rear of one of the Cerberus opened, and a disarmed soldier wearing a special helmet emerged. He barked orders into a square microphone, and two Senti, or Sentinels by their official name, rushed outside. Their thin metal arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted forward. They were armed, but their weapons were attached to their backs.
"Do we kill them or capture them?" asked Craith as they watched them.
"It seems they've captured them," Cohren ventured as the two Sentinels disappeared into a cloud of ash and smoke. Shouts and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but quickly ceased. A moment later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots dragged along the ground. Once safely with the platoon, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed into the mud and snow.
Shaw walked toward the individual, who was beginning to rise. He turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, chief," replied the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned toward Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Both of you, would you kindly get rid of this man?"
